description:
* WHAT...

-For the Winter Storm Warning, heavy snow accumulations of 6 to 14
inches, and winds gusting as high as 40 mph, that can cause reduced
visibility due to blowing snow.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible. Total snow
accumulations of 10 to 25 inches possible, with wind gusts as
high as 45 mph, which could cause reduced visibility due to
blowing snow.

* WHERE...South Central Siskiyou County, including all areas
along I-5 and highway 89, as well as Mt. Shasta City,
Dunsmuir, and McCloud.

* WHEN...For the Winter Storm Warning, from 10 AM this morning
to 10 PM PST this evening. For the Winter Storm Watch, from
Friday afternoon through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Areas
of blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...For the Winter Storm Warning, 1/hr

id: snowfall rates are likely at 80% probability. This period is
concentrated in the 1 PM to 6 PM timeframe. Heavy snow rates
are also expected Friday night during the Winter Storm Watch.
* View the hazard area in detail at

* WHEN...Until 4 AM PST Friday.

* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Above 3000 feet, snow accumulations
10 to 17 inches, with up to 22 inches possible along the peaks
of the volcanoes. Between 2000 and 3000 feet, total snow
accumulations of 5 to 9 inches.

* WHERE...South Washington Cascades.

* WHEN...From midnight tonight to 4 AM PST Friday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snow accumulation will be gradual with the
peak period of snow falling between 10 PM tonight through 12 PM
Thursday. Lingering snow showers will persist through early
Friday morning.

to 60 to 70 mph.

* WHERE...Northern Sweet Grass.

* WHEN...Until 5 AM MST Wednesday.

* WHAT...Strong winds occuring, with brief blizzard conditions
expected. Additional snow accumulations of up to one inch.
Winds gusting as high as 65 mph.

* WHERE...Western Arctic Coast.

* WHEN...Until noon AKST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. Widespread blowing
snow could significantly reduce visibility. Strong winds could
cause damage to building and power lines.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Winds gusting to 90 mph are occuring at
Cape Lisburne. Strong winds to 65 mph are expected to spread to
Point Lay and Wainwright later this morning. Snow will develop
later this morning producing blizzard conditions at times.
Winds are expected to decrease Monday afternoon.

* WHAT...Freezing rain, snow and blowing snow expected.
Additional snow accumulation up to 2 inches and ice
accumulations of around one tenth of an inch. Winds gusting as
high as 65 mph. Visibility one quarter mile o less at times.

* WHERE...Chukchi Sea Coast.

* WHEN...Until noon AKST today.

* IMPACTS...Power outages are likely due to the ice. Travel
could be nearly impossible. Areas of blowing snow could
significantly reduce visibility.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Ice and water may be pushed up on the
shoreline north of Cape Espenberg.

* WHAT...Heavy snow. Additional snow accumulations of 2 to 7
inches, except 6 to 13 inches above 7000 feet. Wind gusts up to
45 mph with waves to 4 feet on Lake Tahoe through tonight.
Sierra ridge gusts up to 90 mph.

* WHERE...Greater Lake Tahoe Area.

* WHEN...Until 1 PM PST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Travel will be very difficult with significant delays
at times over main Sierra travel routes through early Monday
afternoon. Winds and waves could capsize small boats on Lake
Tahoe.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...A lull in snow activity is expected later
this evening through the overnight hours. Additional bands of
heavier snowfall will arrive early Monday morning which will
impact the morning commute.

high as 60 mph.

* WHERE...For the Winter Weather Advisory, areas south of Tennant.
For the Winter Storm Watch. All areas, including highway 97,
Tennant, Bray and Pondosa.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 10 AM this
morning to 10 PM PST this evening. For the Winter Storm Watch,
from Friday afternoon through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...

-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow accumulations up to 4 inches
for elevations above 3500 feet. Winds gusting as high as  45 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible, with
accumulations of 2 to 8 inches possible around the valley floor,
with up to 12 inches in the higher terrain. Winds could gust as
high as 60 mph and is likely to cause reduced from blowing snow.

* WHERE...For the Winter Weather Advisory, the Shasta Valley and
I-5 near Hilt, near the highway 96 & 263 exit, and near Weed.
For the Winter Storm Watch Interstate 5 near Weed, and highway
3 west of Yreka.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 10 AM this
morning to 10 PM PST this evening. For the Winter Storm Watch,
from Friday afternoon through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...

-For the Winter Weather Advisory, Snow expected with accumulations
of 4 to 8 inches, with higher amounts above 4500 feet, and winds
gusting as high as 35 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch above 3000 feet, heavy wet snow
possible, with snow accumulations of 5 to 15 inches. Higher snow
amounts are possible in the higher terrain up to 25 inches.
Winds could gust as high as 50 mph and cause reduced visibility
due to blowing snow.

* WHERE...Western Siskiyou County, including highway 3 south of
Callahan. For the Winter Storm Watch, highway 3 south of Etna and
east of Fort Jones and Sawyers Bar Road west of Etna to Sawyers
Bar.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 10 AM this
morning to 10 PM PST this evening. For the Winter Storm Watch,
from Friday afternoon through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy

hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Gusty winds could bring down tree branches.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...High snowfall rates of 1/hr are likely

-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow expected. Total
snow accumulations of 5 to 10 inches. Winds gusting as high as
45 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible.
Total snow accumulations of 4 to 19 inches possible. Winds
could gust as high as 60 mph.

* WHERE...North Central and Southeast Siskiyou County. This
includes Pondosa, Tennant, and Bray.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

accumulations of 4 to 8 inches expected, with higher amounts
above 4500 feet, and winds gusting as high as 35 mph.

due to blowing snow.

hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Gusty winds could bring down tree branches.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...High snowfall rates of 1/hr are likely

description:
* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow expected. Total
snow accumulations of 5 to 10 inches. Winds gusting as high as
45 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible.
Total snow accumulations of 4 to 19 inches possible. Winds
could gust as high as 60 mph.

* WHERE...North Central and Southeast Siskiyou County. This
includes Pondosa, Tennant, and Bray.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, Snow expected with
accumulations of 4 to 8 inches expected, with higher amounts
above 4500 feet, and winds gusting as high as 35 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch above 3000 feet, heavy wet snow
possible, with snow accumulations of 5 to 15 inches. Higher snow
amounts will be possible in the higher terrain up to 25 inches.
Winds could gust as high as 50 mph and cause reduced visability
due to blowing snow.

* WHERE...Western Siskiyou County, including highway 3 south of
Callahan. For the Winter Weather Watch, this also includes Fort
Jones.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Gusty winds could bring down tree branches.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...High snowfall rates of 1/hr are likely

* WHAT...Snow expected above 4000 feet. Total snow accumulations
of 6 to 12 inches. Winds gusting as high as 35 mph will create
areas of blowing and drifting snow.

* WHERE...Western Siskiyou County above 4000 feet.

* WHEN...From 4 PM Saturday to 10 AM PST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snow will impact primarily rural mountain
areas. However, mountain roads, including Sawyer's Bar Road at
Etna Summit and California highway 3 south of Callahan, will
become snow packed and hazardous, especially at night.

https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...Snow expected above 3500 feet. Total snow accumulations
of 4 to 8 inches with 8 to 16 inches possible above 5000 feet.

* WHERE...South Central Siskiyou County above 3500 feet.

* WHEN...From 4 PM Saturday to 10 AM PST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. The hazardous
conditions could impact the Monday morning commute.

especially at night and during heavier bursts.

county: South End of the Upper Sierra
description:
* WHAT...For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow. Total snow
accumulations of eight to sixteen inches above 5,000 feet. Winds
could gust as high as 60 mph along the crest and through
canyons. For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy snow possible. Total
snow accumulations of two to four feet conceivable above 8,000
feet. Snowfall of one to two feet possible from 7,000 feet to
8,000 feet. Winds could gust as high as 60 mph along the crest
and through canyons.

* WHERE...Southern Sierra Nevada.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, valid until 4 AM PST
Friday morning. For the Winter Storm Watch, valid from Friday
evening through late Sunday night.

* IMPACTS...Travel will be very difficult to impossible. The
hazardous conditions may impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

possible from late afternoon Friday into Friday night.

county: South End of the Upper Sierra
description:
* WHAT...For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow. Additional snow
accumulations of eight to sixteen inches above 5,000 feet. Winds
could gust as high as 60 mph along the crest and through
canyons. For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy snow possible. Total
snow accumulations of two to four feet conceivable above 8,000
feet. Snowfall of one to two feet possible from 7,000 feet to
8,000 feet. Winds could gust as high as 60 mph along the crest
and through canyons.

* WHERE...Southern Sierra Nevada.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, valid until 4 AM PST
Friday morning. For the Winter Storm Watch, valid from Friday
evening through late Sunday night.

* IMPACTS...Travel will be very difficult to impossible. The
hazardous conditions may impact the morning or evening commute.
Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 1 to 3
inches in the lower elevations and 5 to 10 inches in the
higher terrain.

* WHERE...Lower Hells Canyon/Salmon River Region.

* WHEN...Until 5 AM PST Friday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 4 to 11
inches.

* WHERE...Butte, Georgetown Lake, Highway 12 Garrison to
Elliston, Homestake Pass, MacDonald Pass, Highway 200 Bonner
to Greenough, Highway 83 Seeley Lake to Condon, and I-90 East
Missoula to Bearmouth.

* WHEN...Until 6 AM MST Friday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.

Isolated snow showers are still possible today. Most will not
accumulate, but there may be a light dusting above 2000 feet.
